eeds of mythographic discourse in Pindar and Plato, to the mythography of the Peripatics, the in-between mythography of Diodorus Siculus, and the “mythographic topography” of Pausanias, this volume invites a reappraisal of the role that mythography played at every stage of Greek thought about myth. Through contributions that explore both mythographers’ distinctive style of studying myth to other contributions that focus primarily on the how and why of non-mythographers’ use of mythographic techniques, what emerges is a picture of mythography that broadens our conception of mythography while at the same time inviting scholars to seek out more such echoes of mythographic discourse in the work of poets, historians, philosophers at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMythology, ClassicalxHistoriography. 0aMythology, Classical, in literature. 4aGriechische Literatur. 4aLateinische Literatur. 4aMythographie. 4aMythos. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aGreek.  aLatin.  amyth.  amythography.1 aDowden, Ken, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawes, Greta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarincola, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarincola, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNünlist, René, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomano, Allen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomano, Allen J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWissmann, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo